_1":"TH","iso_639_1":"th","name":"ภาษาไทย","english_name":"Thai","data":{"biography":"","name":"Chattiwut Rungrojsuporn","primary":true}}]}},"tv_238585_keywords":{"at":1774693166082,"data":{"id":238585,"results":[{"name":"witch","id":616},{"name":"alternative reality","id":175629},{"name":"murder plot","id":208508}]}},"person_5872279_translations":{"at":1774693168588,"data":{"id":5872279,"translations":[{"iso_3166_1":"US","iso_639_1":"en","name":"English","english_name":"English","data":{"biography":"","name":"Caleb Y Moon","primary":true}}]}},"person_5382024_translations":{"at":1774693173437,"data":{"id":5382024,"translations":[{"iso_3166_1":"US","iso_639_1":"en","name":"English","english_name":"English","data":{"biography":"Evan Bates (born February 23, 1989) is an American ice dancer. With his wife and skating partner, Madison Chock, he is a two-time Olympic gold medalist in the team event (2022, 2026), the 2026 Winter Olympics silver medalist, a three-time World champion (2023, 2024 and 2025), three-time Grand Prix Final champion (2023–24, 2024–25 and 2025–26), a three-time Four Continents champion (2019, 2020, 2023), a twenty-two-time ISU Grand Prix medalist (nine golds, eleven silvers, two bronzes), ten-time ISU Challenger Series medalist (four golds, five silver, one bronze), and a seven-time U.S. national champion (2015, 2020, 2022, 2023, 2024, 2025 and 2026). The two represented the United States at the 2014, 2018, 2022 and 2026 Winter Olympics. He served as flag bearer for the United States during the closing ceremony for the 2026 Winter Olympics.\n\nWith former partner Emily Samuelson, Bates is the 2009 Four Continents bronze medalist, the 2008 World Junior champion, and the 2009 U.S. national silver medalist. They competed at the 2010 Winter Olympics.\n\nDescription above from the Wikipedia article Evan Bates, licensed under CC-BY-SA, full list of contributors on Wikipedia.","name":"Evan Bates","primary":true}}]}},"person_5790470_translations":{"at":1774693176157,"data":{"id":5790470,"translations":[{"iso_3166_1":"US","iso_639_1":"en","name":"English","english_name":"English","data":{"biography":"","name":"Ke Nan","primary":false}}]}},"person_132765_translations":{"at":1774693178942,"data":{"id":132765,"translations":[{"iso_3166_1":"US","iso_639_1":"en","name":"English","english_name":"English","data":{"biography":"Kimiko Ikegami (born January 16, 1959) is a Japanese actress. Born in Manhattan, New York City, she moved to Kyoto at age 3. Kimiko graduated from Horikoshi High School in Nakano, Tokyo and subsequently attended Tamagawa University. She is closely related to the Bandō Mitsugorō kabuki actors: her grandfather was the eighth, her uncle the ninth (later Bandō Minosuke VII), her cousin (Bandō Yasosuke V) the tenth to take that name. With the encouragement of that cousin, Kimiko turned to acting.\n\nShe made her television debut in 1975 in the NHK show Maboroshi no Pen Friend, and in that year also appeared in Ai to Makoto on TV Tokyo. Her entry into film came in 1975, when she appeared in Hadashi no Seishun (Shochiku). In Taiga drama series, Kimiko portrayed Ōhime Kusa Moeru (1979) Chacha (later named Yodo-Dono) in the 1981 Onna Taikō-ki, Lady Tsukiyama (the wife of the title character) in Tokugawa Ieyasu (1983), and Eri (Lady Aburakawa, concubine of the title character) in Takeda Shingen. Other jidaigeki roles have included Sumi in the 1988 NHK Miyamoto Musashi Okon in Tōyama no Kin-san (1989), and Nami in the 2003 TV Tokyo Chūshingura: Ketsudan no Toki. Contemporary roles include the yakuza in Gokudō no Onna-tachi Revenge (the thirteenth in the series) and the female lead in Shiroi Kyotō (TV Asahi, 1990). She appears frequently as a guest star on television series such as Mito Kōmon.\n\nKimiko also recorded a song, Nagasarete, on the Victor Entertainment label. The 1984 release (as of 2006, out of print) was the theme song for the show Kiryūin Hanako no Shōgai.\n\nHer honors include the 1990 Japan Jewellery Association Best Dresser Award.\n\nDescription above from the Wikipedia article Kimiko Ikegami, licensed under CC-BY-SA, full list of contributors on Wikipedia","name":"Kimiko Ikegami","primary":false}},{"iso_3166_1":"JP","iso_639_1":"ja","name":"日本語","english_name":"Japanese","data":{"biography":"","name":"池上季実子","primary":true}},{"iso_3166_1":"CN","iso_639_1":"zh","name":"普通话","english_name":"Mandarin","data":{"biography":"生于纽约曼哈顿，1963年回到日本定居于京都。1974年随家迁往东京，就读于玉川学院高中部。同年被选参加演出NHK电视剧《幻的笔友》，开始涉足艺坛。后转入明星倍出的高中——堀越学院就读，不久即开始其一连串的电影演出，受到广泛关注。1983年在东映电影公司出品的《阳晖楼》里扮演一个叫桃桃若的艺妓，非常成功，使其声名鼎盛。同时也因私生活的不检点而引起众多绯闻，并于1985年怀孕后不得不嫁与一名年近四十的画商。在生下女儿芽实之前，她还拍摄了《危险的女人们》及千叶真一的连续剧《影子军团》。其后演技也更加成熟，如《男女七人夏物语》等。","name":"池上季实子","primary":false}},{"iso_3166_1":"CZ","iso_639_1":"cs","name":"Český","english_name":"Czech","data":{"biography":"","name":"Kimiko Ikegami","primary":false}},{"iso_3166_1":"ES","iso_639_1":"ca","name":"Català","english_name":"Catalan","data":{"biography":"Kimiko Ikegami (Nova York, 16 de gener de 1959) és una actriu japonesa nascuda als Estats Units.","name":"Kimiko Ikegami","primary":false}},{"iso_3166_1":"HK","iso_639_1":"zh","name":"普通话","english_name":"Mandarin","data":{"biography":"生於紐約曼哈頓，1963 年回到日本定居於京都。1974 年隨家遷往東京，就讀於玉川學院高中部。同年被選參加演出 NHK 電視劇《幻的筆友》，開始涉足藝壇。後轉入明星倍出的高中——堀越學院就讀，不久即開始其一聯串的電影演出，受到廣泛關注。1983 年在東映電影公司出品的《陽暉樓》裏扮演一個叫桃桃若的藝妓，非常成功，使其聲名鼎盛。同時也因私生活的不檢點而引起眾多緋聞，並於 1985 年懷孕後不得不嫁與一名年近四十的畫商。在生下女兒芽實之前，她還拍攝了《危險的女人們》及千葉真一的聯續劇《影子軍團》。其後演技也更加成熟，如《男女七人夏物語》等。","name":"池上季實子","primary":false}},{"iso_3166_1":"UA","iso_639_1":"uk","name":"Український","english_name":"Ukrainian","data":{"biography":"","name":"Кіміко Ікеґамі","primary":false}}]}},"person_1494060_translations":{"at":1774693180795,"data":{"id":1494060,"translations":[{"iso_3166_1":"US","iso_639_1":"en","name":"English","english_name":"English","data":{"biography":"Mark Edward Fischbach, better known as Markiplier, is an American YouTuber, gamer-commentator, actor, filmmaker, and comedian. Originally from Honolulu, Hawaii, he began his career in Cincinnati, Ohio, and is currently based in Los Angeles, California. He has expanded his YouTube success into a media career, venturing into acting and filmmaking. His most notable project is the 2026 film adaptation of the equally titled video game Iron Lung, which he wrote, directed, produced, edited and starred in.","name":"Mark Fischbach","primary":true}}]}}}}